s\niry. This -va^ a beautiful event\nthe 1...'hrrun church at eight\nelocx followed by a reception\nr,i ;lar!te a: the country club.\nOr Friay evening Mr. and\nfx. \\had attended a ball\nthe country club given by Mr.\ntd Mrs. A. (i. Peeler, Jr.. in com\nimen: to their sister. Miss Peel\n^nd her fiance, Mr. Hudson,\nrs. Arledge's mother, Mrs. T. C.\n\u25barthn, accompanied them on the\nip j nth-!!* tht time with Mrs.\nC. Finley in Lexington.\n5\n0 CELEBRATE\nOLDEN WEDDING\n\u2022Mr. and Mrs. Sam D. Staton\niii celebrate their golden wed\n!y anniversary on Wednesday,\nfbruary li.'i, at their home on\nChimney Hock road. The\" are\ntten<lii>K a cordial invitation to\n1 f t their friends through this\nium to call between the hours\nthree and five.\n\nenefit helps\nIXTH GRADE\nI At the recent lovely benefit\nstaged under the direction\nf the }frud<* mother, Mrs. W. P.\npdrews, at the Skyland hotel,\nt^.'j\u00bb was cleared for the sixth\nrade librarv at the R\\-;.a Ed\n\u00aenN school, Mrs. M. C. Roberts\nwfher.\nMi Anne Sample, the efficient\nat the public lib-; y. gave\nU\" ot her valuable t:me in as\nking this -p!\u00bb-ndid teacher, Mrs.\nj>'\"rts, in selectin tie books.\n*.v *'ere ordered on Saturday\nwill be a helpful addition to\nlibrary which already has\nttn-v reference as well as other\nlOlW.\n\nASONIC banquet\nOmorrow\nJ\"* hiistei ii Star and Masonic\nr*\"r vv''j stage a delightful\n;ge Washington banquet to\nPl ASH DOwN GO PRICES\n1 WlOIIoN USED RADIOS.\n\u2022Vv us today for sensational\nValues. Terms $1.00 weekly.\nBrunson Furniture Co.\n666\n^'D-TAfiLF.TS\nSalvE-NOSE\nDROPS\nSALVE\nCOLDS\nprice\n10c 25c\nt0NITE TUESDAY\nwill rogers\n'COUNTY\nin\nCHAIRMAN\"\nwith\nLOUISE DRESSER\nmickey rooney\nand\nEVELYN YENABLE\nSTEPIN fetchit\n'Shows at: 2, 4, 7 and 9\nSows on Lpaulet Shoulders\nAdd Gay Charm to Dress\nBY CAROL DAY\n\\TO need to point to the youthful\nA epaulet shoulder on Pattern\n8123 to find its first claim to\ncharm. The bows poised on each\nshoulder and on the front of the\nbodice are quite gay and new.\nThe deep yoke back and front,\nreaching to the waistline, gives\na long, wide look to the bodice\nthat is kind to the figure. The\nskirt flares slightly below the\nnarrow waistline. As a dress for\ndaytime wear, for business and\nschool it can be made up in thin\nwool, in printed crepe or one of\nthe new cottons. Another attrac\ntive feature is that the model is\ndefinitely styled for individuality.\nEven if you are a beginner in\nsewing you can make this dress\nwith confidence. The pattern in\ncludes a complete and detailed\nsew chart that simplifies every\nstep.\nPattern 8123 is designed for\nsizes 12. 14. 16. 18, 20 and 40. Size\n14 reauires 3 5-8 yards of 35 or\n39 inch material pius 2 1-2 yards\nof ribbon for the bows. 2 1-2\nyards of bias fold required to trim\nyoke and sleeves as pictured.\nThe new SPRING AND SUM\nMER PATTERN BOOK, 32 pages\nof attractive designs for every size\nand every occasion, is now readv\nPhotographs show dresses made\nfrom these patterns being worn:\na feature you will enjoy. Let the\ncharming designs in this new\nbook help you in your sewing\nOne pattern and the new Spring\nand Summer Pattern Book\u201425\ntents. Book alone\u201415 cents.\nFor a PATTERN of this attrac\ntive model send 15c in COIN\nyour NAME, ADDRESS, STYLE\nNUMBER and SIZE to TODAY'S\nPATTERN BUREAU, 11 STER\nI TMO PT RROOKTYN N Y\nTo secure a rATTUiKis ana STJUf-ifz-STUi' lNSiKULiiiuxxo\nfill out the coupon below, being sure to mention The Times-News.\nJULIA BOYD, 103 PARK AVENUE, NEW YORK.\nEnclosed is 15 cents in coin for Pattern No Size\nName\nn t\nAddress\nState\nName of this newspaper\nAddress your envelope to Julia Boyd, Times-News Bureau, 103\nPark Avenue, New York City, N. Y.\nmorrow evening at 7:45 at the\nAmes hotel. For last minute res\nervations. call Mrs. Louis Sher\nman at 129-J by tonight.\n\nHERE FOR\nWEEK-END\nIvan Coffey, Bob Childs and\nJimmy Gianakos were here from\nMars Hill college, Mars Hill, for\nthe week-end.\nPERSONAL\nPARAGRAPHS\nMr. and Mrs. Nathan Patla spent\nthe week-end in Charleston, S. C.,\nhaving gone especially to attend\nthe wedding of the former's neph\new, Bernard Olasov, to Miss Har\nriett Tiglar.\nMesdames Arthur Foster, Ed\nBloss and L. Dickson, of Detroit,\nMich., were guests on Saturday of\nMrs?. Rupert Koch en route to\nFlorida.\nMrs. George Cooley, of Ashe\nville, is the guest of Mrs. Nathan\nBrenner.\nMiss Lucius Burrell, who under\nwent an appendix operation Sat\nurday evening at Patton Memor\nial hospital, is reported to be\nmaking satisfactory progress.\nWilliam E. Brackett, Jr., of\nClemson college, Clemson, S. C.,\nwas at home for the week-end.\nMr. and Mrs. Waitsel Dysart, of\nMorganton, were guests yesterday\nof their uncle and aunt, Mr. and\nMrs. J. W. Bailey.\nThomas Hudgens, who is at the\nFrancis Marion Experimental Sta\ntion at Witherbe, S. C.j came for\nan overnight stay.\nMi's. Austin E. Podesta, who\nunderwent an operation recently\nat the Baltimore hospital, is re\ncuperating at the home of Mr.\nPodesta's sister, Mrs. Rupert\nKoch.\nMr. and Mrs. D. 0. Satterfield\nand son, David, are moving to\nday to the Otis Stepp bungalow\non North Main street.\nJONES GAP\n0 O\nJONES GAP, Feb. 21. \u2014Mrs.\nH. H. Mace has returned from\nChester, S. C., where she has\nbeen visiting relatives.\nMack Drake spent Thursday\nnight in Hendersonville with\nfflcisijgiy\nF redric\nMARCH\nin\n\"The Buccaneer'\nwith\nFranciska Gaal\nAkim Tamiroff\n\nfriends.\nArthur Jones has moved from\nthis community and Bluford\nChapel occupied Mr. Jones' form\ner home.\nMr. Pruitt had preaching serv\nice at Mrs. Lula Davis* last Sun\nday evening. Mr. Pruitt give an\nappointment to preach at Mr.\nHeatons near B. B. Blackwell's\nSunday, Feb. 27.\nMr. and Mrs. Albern Drake\nhave moved to D. P. Green's\nplace.\nFederation Opens\n17th Warehouse In\nTransylvania Co.\nBREVARD, Feb. 21.\u2014Estab\nlishment of a Transylvania coun\nty unit of the Farmers Federa\ntion was observed here Saturday\nby the formal opening of the co\nop's 17th warehouse.\nBrief addresses were made by\nJames G. K. McClure, federation\npresident; Guy M. Sales, general\nmanager; Vance A. Browning,\neducational director, and others.\nMusic was supplied by the feder\nation string band.\nThe organization's Brevard\nwarehouse occupies the Allison\nbuilding on East Main street. The\nfederation recently purchased this\nbuilding, a two-story frame struc\nture with basement, and has thor\noughly reconditioned it for use as\na warehouse.\nRobert Caldwell, connected with\nthe Waynesville warehouse of the\nFarmers Federation for the past\ntwo years, has been appointed\nmanager of the Transylvania unit.\nThe Brevard warehouse is the\nsecond opened by the federation\nthis year, a warehouse to serve\nthe farmers of Cherokee and sur\nrounding counties having been\nopened at Murphy February 5.\nAddition of these units adds\nseveral hundred new members or\nstockholders to the farmers' co\noperative and greatly increases its\nterritory.\nEstablished by a handful of\nfarmers in Fairview township,\nBuncombe county, in 1920, tbe\nFarmers Federation has grown\nsteadily since then until it now\nhas approximately 3,500 stock\nholders. Its territory has grown\nfrom a single township to 13\ncounties, in 11 of which it main\ntains warehouses. The volume of\nbusiness has increased from $7,\n000 for the six months the fed\neration operated its first year to\n$1,143,559.67 for 1937.\nBIBLE~STUDY UNIT\nMEETS ON TUESDAY\n\nThe Tuesday Bible study group\nwhich includes members from a\nnumber of denominations in the\ncity, will meet Tuesday morning\nat 10 o'clock at the home of Mrs.\nL. K. Singley in Druid Hills. It\nwas announced that any lady who\nwould be interested, is cordially\ninvited to ojin this group.\nHITLER AND HIS AGENT CONFER\nImmediate and drastic steps to-consolidate the Nasi victory in Austria were expected to follow the\nrush conference, pictured above in photo radioed from Berlin, of Austria's new pro-Nazi Minister of\nthe Interior, Dr. Arthur Seyss-Inquart, with Chancellor Adolf Hitler. Coincidental visits to police\nofficials were considered significant of impending anti-Nazi drive.\nCO.vN GROWERS' CUP\nAND AWARDS GIVEN\n(Continued from natre one)\nI the corn shown in the judging\nSaturday would win prizes in\nI many of the contests held in the\nstate.\nT. H. Stafford, district super\nvisor of agricultural education,\nspoke briefly and brought greet\nings from Roy H. Thomas, state\nsupervisor and others. He intro\nduced vocational teachers as fol\nlows:\nR.*-J. Lyda, Brevard; B. L.\nLunsford, Rosman; E. T. Frisbee,\nMills River; M. E. Nesbitt, Fletch\ner; H. L. Davis, Dana; J. F. Cor\nbin, Hendersonville; W. A. Frank\nlin, Flat Rock; R. B. Bruce, Eto\nwah; T. S. Mulligan, of Edney\nville, and Mr. McCullum, of Bre\nvard college.\nMr. Harrelson was introduced\nby F. H. Jeter, extension editor\nof State college.\nThe speaker confined most of\nhis remarks to a discussion of ade\nquate appropriation by the state\nfor farm research. The three\nfunctions of State college, he said,\nwere resident teaching, extension\nwork, and operation of experi\nmental stations. While North\nCarolina is usually from second\nto fifth in farm income, it is 44th\nin the appropriation for agricul\ntural research. Agriculture, he\nsaid, cannot progress without re\nsearch. When agriculture is\nhealthy, the entire people are in\n1 a healthy economic state.\n\"State college is your institu\ntion just as much as your local\nhigh school,\" he said. \"It can give\nj better instruction if it has funds\nfor research work which cannot\nbe done by individual farmers.\nI The present appropriation is\nabout one-fourth of that neces\nsary to make use of matching\navailable federal funds.\n\"We haven't scratched the sur\nface in North Carolina,\" he said,\nadding that farm resources were\nunexploited bccause of the lack\nof scientific information.\nHe declared the purpose of the\npresent administration to be a\nlai^ef share of the returns from\nraw, materials for the producers,\nthe \"farmers. In this state indus\ntrial income is four times as large\nas farm income although 50 per\ncent of the people make a living\non ,the\\ land.\nHe saw the need as lower pro\nduction costs, new plants and\nfarm aiiimals, and new means of\nusing the state's resources, and\nhe.declared that this could only\nbe done through adequate re\nsearch.\nPictures of farming in Hender\nson county were shown to the\ngroup by S. J. Childs, and includ\ned some made last summer by W.\nF. Algary during the annual farm\ntour. During the interval, L. L.\nBurgin, Henderson representative\nin the general assembly, L. H.\nMcKay, Henderson farmer, and\nE. Carl Allison, Transylvania\nfarmer and commisisoner, were\nrecognized and spoke briefly.\nFollowing the pictures, prizes\nwere awarded to successful con\ntestants as follows:\nJudging of the corn contest by\nvocational agricultural students:\nFirst, Floyd Compton, Transyl\nvania; tied for second, Reid\nLance, Henderson, and J. A. Wild,\nTransylvani; third, Raymond\nNicholson, Transylvania.\nJudging by farmers: First, Carl\nAllison; second, Guy Whitmire;\nthird, G. W. Whitmire, all of\nTransylvania.\nAwards for corn judging were\ncash prizes.\nCorn contest winners:\nYellow corn: First, W. F. How\nman, Henderson; second, L. H.\nMcKay, Henderson; third, Richard\nNorton,* Transylvania; fourth, S.\nR Cathey, Henderson.\njWhite prolific: First, J. D. Hoop\ner,,, Henderson; second, Charles\nBruon, Transylvania; third. J. R.\nSettles, Henderson; fourth, C. F.\nPryor, Henderson; fifth, E. C. Al\nlison, Transylvania; sixth, W. E.\nMoss. Henderson.\nWhite single ear: First, S. P.\nWilliamson, Henderson; second,\nM. E. Settles, Henderson; third,\nG. O. Morgan, Henderson; fourth,\nE. 0. Shipman, Transylvania;\nfifth, Hubert Hyder, Henderson;\nsixths G. W. Whitmire, Transyl\nvania.\nEight thousand pounds of fer\ntilizer and 400 pounds of nitrate\nof soda were distributed to suc\ncessful contestants in the corn\nshow.\nCash awards in the corn produc\ntion contest were then awarded,\nten nrizes being given in each\ncounty. Winners with their yields\nwere;\nHenderson county: First, J. D*\nHooper (176); second, William\nJustice (147); third, O. E. Cor\npening (142); fourth, W. E. Moss\n(138); fifth, Dr, M. Szamatolski\n(129); sixth, Don I.. Hoots (128);\nseventh, Reid Lance (125) eighth,\nJ. M. Goode (121); ninth, S. P.\nWilliamson (115); tenth, Clarence\nGoode (112).\nTransylvania county: Guy Whit\nmire (138.8 bushels, first; Gerald\nAllison (125.2) second; C. C. Al\nlison (llt>) third; E. O. Shipman\ni (101) fourth; Charles Hryson\nI (89) fifth; Herbert Fisher (85)\nsixth; Coy Owens (84) seventh;\nHarry Hog$ett (81) eighth; Jesse\nGlashy (80) ninth, and Cecil Fish\nI er (70) tenth.\nCounty Agent G. I). White to\nday extended his thanks to all\npersons who cooperated in the\nstaging of the second annual corn\nshow and banquet on Saturday.\nMr. White stated that he espe\ncially wished to thank the com\nmercial concerns who gave prizes\nin the form of fertilizer and oth\ner farm materials.\nTWO WAYNESV1LLE\nTEAMS WILL PLAY\nHERE TUESDAY EVE\nThe Hendersonville High Ilas\nketeers will meet the Waynesville\nHigh in a double bill at the city\ngym tomorrow night at 7:30.\nThe Cats lost to Waynesville at\nWaynesville several weeks ago, thie\nboys losing 27 to 26 in a close\ngame and two good games are ex\npected tomorrow.\nSAY TWO JAP SHIPS\nSUNK BY CHINESE\n(Continued from oaee one)\ntions are pouring into Hankow,\nand the motor routes through\nnorthwest China into Soviet Rus\nsia.\nMore than 500,000 Chinese and\nJapanese soldiers were engaged in\na series of battles in the railway\nrectangle north of the Yangtse\nriver with the Chinese still hold\ning Hsuchow-Fu, key city in the\nlower Tieritsin-Pukow (Nanking)\nrailway sector and the 100 mile\nleg of the southern Peiping-Han\nkow railway from Chengchow to\nHankow, where the Lunghai rail\nway crosses the \"Ping-Han\" line.\nCanton reported Japanese squad\nrons totaling more than 30 planes\nbombed the Cantno-Hankow rail\nway throughout Sunday and raid- j\ned Chinese barracks and munitions\ndumps in villages and towns along\nthe line.\nThe Japanese attributed their\nincreasing difficulties in the air\nto the \"fact that Soviet Russians\nhave taken over complete control\nof the Chinese air force.\"\nThe well-informed Peiping cor\nrespondent of the Tokyo newspa\nper Asahi said that P.ussians had\nbeen reorganizing the Chinese air\nforce since January 1 and that\nSoviet experts were training Chi\nnese pilots and assembling Soviet\nmade planes at Hankow, Chang\nsha and other Chinese air fields.\nThe Japanese claimed to have\noccupied a number of additional\nlarge towns in southern Shansi\nprovince during the week end and\nto have smashed the former Chi\nnese communist armies in this\narea. I\nEDEN OF ENGLAND,\nQUITS CABINET,\n(Continued from pace one)\nof \"Mussolini has triumphed over\nhis oJd foe!\"\nObservers believed that the res\nignations of Eden and Cranborne\nwere only the signal for a graver\ngovernment crisis, that will burst\nin full blast when Eden and\nChamberlain appear in the\nHouse of Commons to explain\ntheir positions.\nEden, in high anger, was ex\npected to accuse his erstwhile col\nleague of embarking on a \"cow\nardly surrender\" to the dictators,\nand repudiating the principles of\nthe League of Nations.\nThe government, to justify its\npolicy which forced Eden's resig\nnation, must now sidetrack his\ninsistence on withdrawal of the\n40,000 or 45,000 Italian \"volun\nteers\" fighting in Spain, stopping\nof Italian anti-British propagan\ndo in the far east and other \"in\nternatoinal\" measures to drive di\nrectly toward a new friendship\nwith Mussolini.\nII Duce's prime demand as the\nprice of new Anglo-Italian friend\nship, formally conveyed to Cham\nberlain last Friday, is British rec\nognition of Italy's conquest of\nEthiopia. Eden had opposed,\nalong with France, such recogni\ntion in months of bartering.\nAccording to estimates, in one\nout of every four murder cases\nthe guilty person takes his own\nlife.\nThree From Here\nAt Medical Meet\nDrs. L. B. McDonald, Pierre\nMallett and W. N. Fortoscuc of\nHendersonville arc attending tin\n4()th annual meeting of the Tii\nStatc Medical association, com\nprising the Carolina.* and Vir\nginia, now in session at (Jrove\nPark inn in Ashcvillc.\nNumbers of doctors in Western\nNorth Carolina are expected t\u00ab\u00bb\nattend the sessions.\nThe program opened this morn\ning at 9 a. m. and will continue\nthrough Tuesday afternoon. A\nnumber of outstanding medical\nmen from the three states will\nappeal- on the program, and the\nreading of papers will be follow\ned by discussions.\nA joint meeting with the Bun\ncombe county association will be\nheld tonight at 8 o'clock.\n'MIND' IS SUBJECT\nOF SCIENCE CHURCHES\n\"Mind\" was the subject of the\nlesson-sermon in all Christian\nScience Churches and Societies\non Sunday, February 20, 1938.\nThe golden text was from\nPsalms 92:5: \"0 Lord, how gretit\nare thy works; and they thoughts\nare very deep.\"\nAmong the citations which\ncomprised the lesson-sermon was\nthe following from the Bible:\n\"And one of the scribes came,\nand having heard them reasoning\ntogether, and perceiving that he\nhad answered them well, asked\nhim, Which is the first command\nment of all? And Jesus answered\nhim, The first of all the com\nmandments is, Hear, O Israel;\nThe Lord our God is one Lord:\nAnd thou shalt love the Lord thy\nGod with all thy heart, and with\nall thy soul, and with all thy\nmind, and with all thy strength:\nthis is the first commandment\"\n(Mark 12:28-30).\nThe lesson-sermon also includ\ned the following passage from the\nChristian Science textbook, \"Sci\nence and Health with Key to the\nScriptures\" by Mary Baker Eddy:\n\"It should be thoroughly under\nstood that all men have one\nMind, one God and Father,- one\nLife, Truth, and Love. Mankind\nwill become perfect in proportion\nas this fact becomes apparent,\nwar will cease and the true\nbrotherhood of man will he estab\nlished. Having no other gods,\nturning to no other but the one\nperfect Mind to guide him, man\nis the likeness of God, pure and\neternal, having that Mind which\nwas also in Christ\" (page 4f\u00bb7).\nLOCAL HOUSING\nUNIT IS PUNNED\n(Continued from rage one)\nmodernization campaign under\nliberal federal loans.\nMr. Bennett ^ffered his serv\nices upon acceptance of the fol\nlowing telegram from Stewart-[\nMcDonald, federal housing admin\nistrator of Washington, I). C.:\n\"The passage of the new na\ntional housing act opens the way\nfor a real residential construc-i\ntion program which should carry\nwith it a genuine business revival.\nThe president asks that we again\nrequest your participation as vol\nuntary chairman to organize a\nbetter housing committee to im-j\nmediately sponsor this revival in\nyour community and get its full\nbenefits immediately. Please wire\nme collect if you accept and let\nter outlining plan will immediate\nly follow.\n\"Stewart McDonald, federal\nhousing administrator.\"\nfrancTwTll OPPOSE\nPLANS FOR EXPANSION\ni\n(Continued from p.ipre one)\ntion for immediate construction\nof more warolanes and two more\n35,000-ton battleships.\nThe seriousness with which\nFrance regards the situation was.\nshown by the swiftness of the\ngovernment's moves.\nBesides the seriousness of the 1\nAustro-German and Czechoslo- j\nvakian situations the course of\nFrench action was complicated l\u00bby\nthe sudden resignation of the\nBritish foreign secretary, An\nthony Eden, who has been a\nchampion of close Anglo-French\naction in dealing with European\naffairs.\n\nOnly one of- the 93 elements in\nhe universe is unknown; dement\nNo. K7 is worth $4,000,000 a I\npound.\nJ. IPITT1LL0\nPASSES AWAY\nFuneral for Fruitland Sec\ntion Resident Will\nBe Tuesday\nJames Merrimon Pittillo. \u00ab>G,\nfarmer nf tho Fruitland sect:on,\ndied at his home yesterday after\nnoon after an illness of several\nmonths.\nFuneral services will bo con\nducted at the late residence on\nTuesday afternoon .it 2 o'clock\nby the Rev. Vomer, and burial\nwill follow in tho Pittillo ceme\ntery.\nA native of Henderson county,\nMr. Pittillo is survived by his wid\now and several children.\nMr. Pittillo was the son of the\nlate Mr. and Mrs. J. L. Pittillo.\nHe suffered a heart attack Christ\nmas day and had not recovered\nfrom this.\nHis widow was the former Miss\nMary Myers, of Franklin, and to\ntheir marriage wore born five chil\ndren. Mary, Atwood. Joyce, Jeane,\nand a surviving infant, all of whom\nare at home.\nMr. Pittillo was twice married,\nhis first wife bein^ the former\nMiss Jennie Myers, who was a na\ntive of Buncombe county. He sur\nvived her by about 12 years. Born\nto this union were Raymond Pit\ntillo, of Virginia, and Norman,\nresident of this county.\nSurviving brothers are J. B.t\nW. R., S. J., and 7.. V. Pittillo,\nand two sisters, Mrs. Alice Taylor\nof Biltmorc, and Mrs. Mattie Mc\nCulloun'h of Druid Hills also sur\nvive.\nU. S. POLICY IS NOT\nCHANGED BY SHIFT\n(Continued from page one)\nEmnire in event of war.\nThrough the expeditious use of\nsuch power, Dodd was quoted, the\nRoman Eagle could exact tremen\ndous concessions from Britain.\nDodd's testimony was given be\nI fore Reichsfuehrer Adolf Hitler's\n1 Nazification of Austria.\nHe assertedly told the commit\ntee that Germany and Italy prob\nably would not resort to arms ex-j\neept as a last means of uaininjr\ntheir objectives. He said that Ja\npan is a most important consid\neration in activities of the Rome\ni Berlin axis and predicted that the\nisland empire would come to the\naid of the two European Fascist\npowers immediately in event of a\nmajor war.\ni Dodd also testified that war be\ntween Germany and Italy is en\ntirely conceivable because of jeal\nousy resulting from one nation\nobtaining more than the other.\nHo said a boycott of the \"have\nnot\" powers by the \"haves\" would\ncrush Germany. Italy and Japan,\nbut added that the horrors of the\nlast war are still so fresh in the\nj memories of the British, French\nand American governments that'\nI thev are afraid to act.\nWith this knowledge, he was i\nI quoted, Hitler and Mussolini will\ngo the limit to gain sources of,\nraw materials and mom for ex\nnnnsion in Europe and northern\nAfrica.\nOne of Great Britain's ereatest\ndifficulties, Dodd reportedly testi\nfied. is the fact that the empire\nactually is loose confederation\nof states, some of which might re\nfuse to bear arms in defense of\nthe motherland in event of a Eu\nro nean war.\nHe said the overwhelming paci\nfist sentiment of the major powers\nwas largely resnonsible for the\nwar-like, agjrressive moves of some\nof the dissatisfied nations. He pre\ndicted that in any realignment of\npowers, Russia undoubtedly would\nbe found in the camp of the i\n\"haves\" against the \"have nots,\" t\nand added that recent Soviet pol\nicy has been slanted towards\nfriendliness with the democratic\nnations.\nIt was learned that Dodd charged\nthat after the Inter-American\npeace conference at Buenos Aires\nlate in 193(5, Germany sent secret\nagents to the Argentine capital to\nundermine the good will engen\ndered by President Roosevelt's and\nSecretary of State Cordell Hull's\nvisits.\n5 CASES ACTED ON\nIN MAYOR'S COURT\nSeveral cases were heard in\ncity court this morning before\nMayor A. V. Edwards. The dock-1\net was as follows:\nArthur Allison, drunk and dis\norderly, was fined $10 and costs.\nBob Smith, drunk and disorder\nly, was sentenced to serve .'JO\ndays.\nMont Nelson, drunk and disor\nderly, was sentenced to serve 30\ndays.\nClyde Anderson, drunk and dis\norderly, was fined $10 and costs.\nHugh Anderson, drunk and dis\norderly, was fined $10 and costs.\nMOUNTAIN PAGE\nBENEFIT PLANNED\nA chicken supper will 